\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Improving the resolution of NaI based 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 detector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Prashansa Gupta, Vivek Sagar and Atul Singh Arora
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
November 13, 2014
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Theory/Procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theory and procedure for the experiment for a given voltage is the same
 as that described in the experiment titled `
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 spectrum using NaI detector'.
 The only new assumption made in this experiment has been described here.
 We start with defining 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\equiv\frac{\text{Full Width at Half Maxima}}{\text{Height of the peak}}
\]

\end_inset

and resolution as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\equiv1/\sigma
\]

\end_inset

The assumptions made are that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists a unique operating voltage (the voltage supplied to the photo-multi
plier) 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 the resolution, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is highest in its neighborhood
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The resolution 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 doesn't depend on the voltage at which the peak (before electronic linear
 amplification/attenuation) is obtained, viz.
 the operating voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 gives the highest resolution for all radioactive sources available in the
 lab.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we need only plot the resolution (
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

) as a function of various operating voltages 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and find the minima from the graph.
 This yields 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 which is recommended to be used in subsequent experiments, granted the
 assumptions are valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NB: We were never able to explicitly test if the second assumption holds
 as the graph with Cobalt couldn't be obtained in accordance with known
 results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Observations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset External
	template PDFPages
	filename plotting resolution char compiled.pdf
	extra LaTeX "pages={1,2}"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operating voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 was found to be roughly 420 V.
\end_layout

